In [16]:
def percentages(column):
    percnt = []
    jobs = []
    for val in df[column].unique():
        yes = ((df[column]==val) & (df.Target=='yes')).sum()
        no  = ((df[column]==val) & (df.Target=='no')).sum()    
        jobs.append((val,round((yes/(yes+no))*100)))    
    df1 = pd.DataFrame(jobs,columns=[column,'Percentage Deposited'])
    return df1.sort_values(by=['Percentage Deposited'],ascending=False)

EDA Summary¶

  1. Numeric variables are age, balance, day, duration, campaign, pdays, previous, poutcome.
  2. Categorical variables are job, marital, education, default, housing, loan, contact, month, and poutcome.
  3. The ‘pdays’ column has 81.74% of the values as -1. The value could mean that the number of days passed could either be 0 or greater than 900 days. We do not know exactly if -1 could be changed to 0 or 900, hence we cannot impute them. We also cannot drop these rows because that would mean losing 81.74% of the rows. Hence we can remove the pout column.
  4. The day column represents the day of the month. If we combine this column with the “month” column then later on making dummy variables would cost a lot of resources. So we will drop this column and only keep the “month” column.
  5. Multivariate analysis between job and the target variables tells us that students have the highest percentage of subscribing for a term deposit, followed by retired personals.
  6. Singles have a high percentage of subscribing for a term deposit.
  7. Of all the months in a year, people last contacted in March, Sept, October and December have the highest prevalence of deposit subscription.
  8. People with successful previous campaign have a prevalence of deposit subscription of 65%.
  9. People with no credit in default have double the prevalence of deposit subscription than those who have credit in default.
  10. People with no loan have double the prevalence of deposit subscription than those who have loan on them.
  11. Marital status, mode of contact, education does not seem to have much impact.
  12. People with high balance have lesser chance of term deposit.
  13. People with high amount of contacts during this campaign have lesser chance of subscribing to the term deposit. Similar is the case with number of contacts during the previous campaign
  14. The target variable, which tells if the customer opted for deposit or not is imbalanced. Only around 11.69% of the values are "yes".

The F1 score is not very good in all the models. This is due to low recall value, which means the model has high false negatives. High false negatives is because the target variable only contains around 11.69% of the values as "yes". All the models have low recall value but Bagging with Decision Tree has the best precision, recall, F1 Score and accuracy. Hence, Bagging with Decision Tree here is the best overall model.
